items.synopsis: It's do or die for Carlton and Sydney as they meet under the Friday night lights at the MCG for an elimination final not to be missed. Follow the action in our live blog.

title.children: Blues on the verge of breakthrough finals win, but gutsy Swans set up grandstand finish

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: A red hot start from Carlton, a controlled spell of Sydney dominance and then a late sucker-punch from the Blues. The Swans will be hoping they aren't following in Melbourne's footsteps from last night, as they have left a number of good chances on the table already — though none as clear-cut as Harry McKay's miss from the top of the goalsquare. Intriguing game here. Carlton will be happy to be leading, but much too early to have read on which way this one is going.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Quarter-time: Blues lead it by nine points

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Word has come down from the AFL this evening confirming Collingwood's Brayden Maynard will face the tribunal on Tuesday night for his hit on Melbourne's Angus Brayshaw. It means Maynard is potentially facing a season-ending suspension of three games or more. The AFL's statement also made it clear that the AFL's new GM of Football Laura Kane was involved in the decision, which is highly unusual. Melbourne's Jacob van Rooyen was also offered a one-game ban for his elbow on Dan McStay. But this Maynard case is going to be the big story of the weekend, and likely all of next week too. This one is only just beginning.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Brayden Maynard is off to the tribunal

image.altText: An NRL player is surrounded by teammates after scoring, screaming in excitment to the crowd.

items.synopsis: The Brisbane Broncos will host a preliminary final after defeating the Melbourne Storm 26-0 at Lang Park. Follow live.

title.children: Broncos break 14-year drought against Melbourne, as luckless Storm superstar suffers another ugly injury

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: The Broncos have flashed their premiership credentials with a 26-0 win over the Storm, and that big, fat zero will be the most satisfying part of booking their ticket to the preliminary final. Melbourne was a rabble in attack, but that didn't come out of nowhere. Brisbane's defence was up in their face from the opening hit-up, with Pat Carrigan leading the way. They rushed the Storm and forced them into bad decisions, which dug Melbourne into a hole, which begat more errors, which dug the hole deeper. Pure joy for the Broncos, who are through to their first preliminary final since 2017.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Brisbane finally take down Melbourne on a miserable night for the Storm

children.content: (Getty)

They rushed the Storm and forced them into bad decisions, which dug Melbourne into a hole, which begat more errors, which dug the hole deeper.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Are you kidding me? Ryan Papenhuyzen is flattened by a charging Tom Flegler and comes out of the tackle in major distress. The injury is visible is all I'll say. They've called for the medicab immediately. Looked like Storm teammate Nelson Asofa-Solomona swung around in the tackle and pinned his foot under him, causing a horrible break. Seven minutes to go, the match gone, and this has happened to a man who's only in his third game back after a devastating shattered kneecap that kept him out of the game for more than a year. The injury is actually sustained in exactly the same area on the field as the Jack Wighton collision that busted his knee last year. This poor bloke, after more than a year out of the game he loves, now looks set for another incredibly long, painful stint on the sidelines. He's in tears has he leaves the field. His teammates and opposition all look incredibly distressed. Cruel. Unfair. It doesn't say enough.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Ryan Papenhuyzen is down with an ugly ankle injury
